"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 23–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-23-24.py

Key decisions in this range:
- ch.23 (Woes Discourse): classified throughout as direct revelation — Jesus speaks
  as the authoritative judge of the covenant community, the one who knows what the
  Father requires; the seven woes are the inverse of the eight beatitudes
- 23:8-12: the community-forming claims ("you have one teacher, one Father, one
  instructor, the Christ") are the most explicit Christological self-identification
  in the discourse
- 23:34-36: Jesus speaks as the sender of prophets ("I send you prophets") — the
  divine prerogative of commissioning prophecy
- 23:37-39: Lament over Jerusalem is direct revelation — Jesus speaks as divine Wisdom
  (cf. Prov 8; Wis 10) who gathers the children; the "I" who would have gathered
  is the pre-incarnate and incarnate Son
- ch.24 (Olivet Discourse): classified as direct revelation throughout — Jesus is
  the Son of Man who will return (Dan 7:13-14); he has authority to predict and
  inaugurate the eschatological events he describes
- 24:30-31: the Son of Man coming on the clouds is the peak Christological claim
  of the discourse — direct citation of Dan 7:13 applied to Jesus' personal return
- 24:35: "heaven and earth will pass away but my words will not" — direct revelation
  of the eternal authority of the Son's words
- 24:36: the Father's exclusive knowledge of the hour is a genuine humility-claim
  of the incarnate Son (not a diminishment of divinity)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "23": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus said to the crowds and to his disciples..." The Woes Discourse (ch.23) is addressed to the broadest possible audience — crowds and disciples together — before the private Olivet Discourse (ch.24) to the inner circle. The Christological address: the one who pronounces the woes is not a Pharisaic rival but the one with the authority to judge the covenant community\'s teachers. The discourse is the last public teaching before the passion.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "The scribes and the Pharisees sit on Moses\' seat." The acknowledgment of the scribes\' and Pharisees\' seat of authority — Moses\' seat (<em>kathedra Mōyseōs</em>) — is the Christological concession: their teaching office is real. The Christological problem is not their authority but the gap between their words and their lives. Jesus does not deny the office; he exposes the occupants\' failure to embody what the office requires.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "So do and observe whatever they tell you, but not the works they do. For they preach, but do not practice." The command to obey the teaching but not imitate the behavior is the Christological distinction between office and character. The scribes\' interpretation of Torah is in many respects correct; their failure is the gap between proclamation and life. The Christological irony: the one who commands obedience to those who "preach but do not practice" is himself the one who embodies everything he teaches.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "They tie up heavy burdens, hard to bear, and lay them on people\'s shoulders, but they themselves are not willing to move them with their finger." The heavy burdens of Pharisaic interpretation are the Christological contrast to 11:28-30 (Jesus\' "easy yoke" and "light burden"). The one who diagnoses the unbearable burden of accumulated oral law is the same one who offers himself as the burden\'s alternative. The Christological gospel is embedded in the woe: because they burden, he lightens.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "They do all their deeds to be seen by others. For they make their phylacteries broad and their fringes long." The performance religion — phylacteries enlarged to signal piety, fringes lengthened for visibility — is the Christological exposure of the externalist mistake. The one who announced "your Father who sees in secret will reward you" (6:6) now identifies those whose religion is structured for human rather than divine observation. The display is the opposite of the prayer-closet.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they love the place of honor at feasts and the best seats in the synagogues." The love of honor — places of distinction at feasts and in worship — is the Christological exposure of the ladder-climbing that replaces the child-in-the-center (18:2). The one who took the lowest place (Phil 2:7-8) describes those who compete for the highest. The kingdom\'s inversion is stated negatively here: those who love honor receive the woe that corresponds to their desire.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "And greetings in the marketplaces and being called rabbi by others." The title-seeking — "Rabbi, Rabbi" in public spaces — is the Christological exposure of identity built on human recognition. The one who receives worship from the disciples and the crowds without seeking it exposes the self-promotion of those who arrange to be addressed honorifically. The title "Rabbi" is being used as a means of social elevation rather than as a description of genuine service.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "But you are not to be called rabbi, for you have one teacher, and you are all brothers." The "you have one teacher" (<em>heis estin hymin ho didaskalos</em>) is the Christological claim: the disciples have one teacher — Jesus himself. The prohibition of the title Rabbi in the community is not false modesty but accurate theology: the only genuine teacher is the one who taught as one with authority (7:29), the Son who alone knows the Father (11:27). All other teaching is derivative.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "And call no man your father on earth, for you have one Father, who is in heaven." The prohibition of the "Father" title in religious authority is grounded in the Christological theology of the one Father who is in heaven. The one who taught the disciples to pray "Our Father in heaven" (6:9) and who knows the Father exclusively (11:27) is the source of this prohibition. All human fatherhood in the spiritual sense is derived from and subordinate to the one divine Father.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "Neither be called instructors, for you have one instructor, the Christ." The third prohibition — "you have one instructor, the Christ" — is the most explicit Christological self-identification in the discourse. Jesus identifies himself as "the Christ" (<em>ho Christos</em>), the anointed one, the Messiah who is the community\'s sole authoritative guide. The disciples are not to receive the title "instructor" because the Instructor — the Messiah — is present. All other instruction exists under his authority.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "The greatest among you shall be your servant." The greatness-through-service principle (cf. 20:26-27) is restated as the direct alternative to the Pharisaic honor-seeking. The Christological embodiment: the one who pronounces this is about to wash no feet (John 13) and give his life as a ransom for many (20:28). The discourse between the two actions of service and sacrifice. The principle is not merely a community rule but the description of the Messiah\'s own trajectory.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "Whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted." The reversal-principle of the kingdom (cf. 20:16; Luke 14:11; 18:14) is the Christological law of the new order. The one who pronounces it will undergo both movements himself: humbled at the cross (Phil 2:8: "he humbled himself, becoming obedient to the point of death"), and exalted at the resurrection (Phil 2:9: "God has highly exalted him"). The principle is autobiographical as well as prescriptive.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "But woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you shut the kingdom of heaven in people\'s faces. For you neither enter yourselves nor allow those who would enter to go in." The first woe pronounces the ultimate Christological judgment: those who close the kingdom against others. The kingdom of heaven is precisely what Jesus has been announcing and offering throughout his ministry; those who shut it close the door that Christ has opened. The gatekeepers who lock out the seekers are the adversaries of the mission Jesus has come to accomplish.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: (v.14, about devouring widows\' houses, is absent from the best manuscripts but present in the Received Text tradition as a second woe.) The devouring of widows\' houses under the cover of religious performance is the exploitation of the vulnerable by those who hold the levers of religious authority. Whether original or a harmonization from Mark 12:40 / Luke 20:47, it captures a pattern Jesus consistently condemns: religion as a cover for exploitation.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you travel across sea and land to make a single proselyte, and when he becomes a proselyte, you make him twice as much a child of hell as yourselves." The Christological indictment of proselytism without transformation: the convert who is trained in the Pharisaic system is doubly formed by it. The "child of hell" (<em>huios geennēs</em>) — literally "son of Gehenna" — is the eschatological judgment on the outcome of religion-without-repentance. The missionary zeal is real; the product is doubly corrupted.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, blind guides, who say, \'If anyone swears by the temple, it is nothing, but if anyone swears by the gold of the temple, he is bound by his oath.\'" The third woe exposes the casuistry of oath-interpretation: elaborate distinctions between binding and non-binding oaths that create loopholes for evasion. The Christological authority: Jesus is the one who commanded "let your yes be yes and your no be no" (5:37) — the simplicity of a life lived in the presence of the God from whom nothing is hidden.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "You blind fools! For which is greater, the gold or the temple that has made the gold sacred?" The Christological logic: the gold is sacred because of the Temple, not vice versa. The casuistry that binds by the gold but not the Temple has confused derivative and source. The one who knows the Temple is his Father\'s house (21:13) knows what makes gold sacred: the divine presence that the Temple signifies.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "And you say, \'If anyone swears by the altar, it is nothing, but if anyone swears by the gift that is on the altar, he is bound by his oath.\'" The same casuistic pattern applied to the altar and its gifts is the second example of oath-hierarchy manipulation. The Christological exposure: the elaborate system of binding-and-loosing around oaths has been constructed to enable deception while maintaining legal cover.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "You blind men! For which is greater, the gift or the altar that makes the gift sacred?" The same argument as v.17: the altar sanctifies the gift, not the reverse. The Christological hermeneutic appeals to the logic of holiness: what makes anything sacred is its relationship to the holy God, not its intrinsic value or the category it is placed in.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "So whoever swears by the altar swears by it and by everything on it." The correction of the casuistry sweeps away the distinctions: the altar and the gift, the temple and the gold, are bound together. There is no valid loophole. The Christological simplicity: the one who commands plain speech cuts through the elaborate evasion-system with the logic of what makes anything sacred.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "And whoever swears by the temple swears by it and by him who dwells in it." The divine dwelling in the Temple — "him who dwells in it" — is the ultimate sanction behind all Temple-oaths. The Christological identity: the one speaking is the one in whom the divine presence dwells in a more complete sense than in the Temple (cf. John 1:14: "the Word dwelt among us"; 2:19-21: "he was speaking about the temple of his body").</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "And whoever swears by heaven swears by the throne of God and by him who sits on it." The heavenly throne and the one who sits on it is the final sanction behind all oaths — whether people recognize it or not. The Christological bearing: the one who sits on the heavenly throne (Rev 4-5; Dan 7:9) is the one before whom all speech and all oath-evasion is naked and exposed. The casuistry collapses when the throne is in view.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you tithe mint and dill and cumin, and have neglected the weightier matters of the law: justice and mercy and faithfulness. These you ought to have done, without neglecting the others." The fourth woe identifies the category error: meticulous tithing of garden herbs while neglecting justice, mercy, and faithfulness. The Christological priority: the "weightier matters" (<em>ta baryteron</em>) are the matters of covenant character — exactly what the Sermon on the Mount addressed. The Messiah who announces these is the one who embodies justice, mercy, and faithfulness perfectly.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "You blind guides, straining out a gnat and swallowing a camel!" The gnat-and-camel image is the Christological exposure of misplaced precision: obsessive concern with the smallest impurities (gnats were filtered from wine to prevent swallowing an unclean insect) while the largest violation (injustice, faithlessness) goes unchallenged. The one who identifies the inversion has the authority of the covenant\'s author: the Torah\'s intent was justice and mercy, not herb-tithing precision.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you clean the outside of the cup and the plate, but inside they are full of greed and self-indulgence." The fifth woe — the inside/outside distinction — is the Christological diagnosis of exteriorism: ritual cleanliness maintained while the interior is full of predatory desire. The one who taught "what comes out of the mouth proceeds from the heart" (15:18) identifies the cup\'s interior as the domain of genuine purity. The heart cannot be cleaned by washing the cup.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "You blind Pharisee! First clean the inside of the cup and the plate, that the outside also may be clean." The call to inside-first cleanliness is the Christological order of transformation: genuine purity works from the inside out, not the outside in. The new heart promised in Ezek 36:26 is the inside cleaning that produces genuine external righteousness. The Messiah who speaks this is himself the agent of the inside cleaning he prescribes.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you are like whitewashed tombs, which outwardly appear beautiful, but within are full of dead people\'s bones and all uncleanness." The sixth woe — the whitewashed tomb — is the most vivid of the Christological images: beautiful exterior concealing corpse-uncleanness. Tombs were whitewashed before Passover to prevent accidental defilement by contact with the dead. The Pharisaic system is the religious equivalent: beautiful and ceremonially pure on the outside, spiritually dead within.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "So you also outwardly appear righteous to others, but within you are full of hypocrisy and lawlessness." The Christological verdict names the interior condition: hypocrisy (acting a part) and lawlessness (<em>anomia</em> — the same word used in 7:23 for those who are excluded from the kingdom despite prophesying in Jesus\' name). The gap between appearance and reality is the condition Jesus consistently exposes, because the Father "who sees in secret" (6:6) sees what the appearance conceals.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you build the tombs of the prophets and decorate the monuments of the righteous." The seventh woe begins with the apparently pious act of honoring the dead prophets. The Christological trap: the same generation that honors dead prophets is about to kill the living one. The tomb-building for the prophets is the alibi of those who are continuing the pattern of prophet-rejection in real time.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "Saying, \'If we had lived in the days of our fathers, we would not have taken part with them in shedding the blood of the prophets.\'" The historical disclaimer — "we would not have done what our fathers did" — is the self-exculpation that Jesus will puncture. Every generation believes it would have recognized the prophets when they arrived; every generation has the chance to prove this — and Jesus\' generation is failing the test.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "Thus you witness against yourselves that you are sons of those who murdered the prophets." The self-witness of the Pharisees — affirming that the fathers murdered the prophets — implicates them in the same lineage. The Christological family tree: "sons of those who murdered" names the generational continuity not as genetic inevitability but as chosen pattern. They are completing the pattern of their fathers, not escaping it.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "Fill up, then, the measure of your fathers." The command to "fill up the measure" is the Christological irony of divine permission: the cup of iniquity that has been accumulating across generations will be completed in this generation\'s rejection of the Son. The passion Jesus is about to undergo is the generation\'s filling of the measure — the completion of the long pattern of prophet-rejection, now extended to the Son himself.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: "You serpents, you brood of vipers, how are you to escape being sentenced to hell?" The serpent-language echoes John the Baptist\'s address (3:7: "brood of vipers") — the same prophetic condemnation applied to the same generation. The Christological progression: John condemned; now Jesus, speaking as the one who will judge, asks the rhetorical question: how will they escape Gehenna? The answer, implicit, is that they will not escape unless they repent.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore I send you prophets and wise men and scribes, some of whom you will kill and crucify, and some you will flog in your synagogues and drive from town to town." The "I send you" (<em>egō apostellō</em>) is the Christological claim of divine prerogative: only God sends prophets (Amos 3:7; Jer 7:25). Jesus takes the divine role of the sender of prophets — the same role he will give the risen Son in 28:18-20 (the Great Commission). The list of persecutions (kill, crucify, flog, drive from town to town) is the history of the early church already present in prophetic foreknowledge.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A direct revelation: "So that on you may come all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah the son of Barachiah, whom you murdered between the sanctuary and the altar." The range from Abel to Zechariah spans the entire Hebrew Bible — the first and last murder recorded in the canonical sequence (Gen 4:8; 2 Chr 24:21). The Christological judgment: this generation will complete the arc of violence against the righteous, and the blood of all will be required of it. The one who pronounces this judgment knows that his own blood is next in the sequence.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, all these things will come upon this generation." The specification "this generation" (<em>hē genea hautē</em>) is the Christological targeting of the judgment on the generation that will reject the Son. The destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD is the historical fulfillment. The Christological precision: Jesus does not speak abstractly about future judgment but concretely about the generation to which he is speaking.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to it! How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, and you were not willing!" The Christological lament is the most tender moment in the Woes Discourse — the severity of judgment replaced by the anguish of love. "How often would I have gathered you" — the divine Wisdom who seeks her children (Prov 8; Wis 10), the YHWH who would shelter Israel "under his wings" (Ps 36:7; 91:4; Ruth 2:12) — is identified with Jesus. The pre-incarnate Son longed to gather Jerusalem across the entire OT period.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "See, your house is left to you desolate." The "your house" (<em>ho oikos hymōn</em>) — no longer "my house" (21:13) — is the Christological withdrawal: the Temple is abandoned by the divine presence. The desolation (<em>erēmos</em>) echoes Jer 22:5 and the prophetic warnings of Shekinah-departure from the Temple (Ezek 10:18-19; 11:22-23). The Son who wept over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) pronounces its desolation with the authority of the one who gave it its significance.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "For I tell you, you will not see me again, until you say, \'Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord.\'" The "you will not see me again" until the eschatological welcome is the Christological pause: after the crucifixion and resurrection, Jesus will not appear publicly to Jerusalem in the same way. The future welcome — "blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord" (Ps 118:26, the Hosanna of 21:9) — is the eschatological reception of the returning Son, when Jerusalem will recognize the one it rejected. The lament holds open the door of future mercy even as it pronounces present desolation.'
  },
  "24": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus left the temple and was going away, when his disciples came to point out to him the buildings of the temple." The departure from the Temple — the day after the Woes Discourse — marks the Christological withdrawal announced in 23:38 ("your house is left to you desolate"). The disciples\' pointing to the magnificent buildings is the response of those whose category for "kingdom" is still architectural and institutional. The one who called it "my Father\'s house" (21:13) and then "your house" (23:38) is now leaving it permanently.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "But he answered them, \'You see all these, do you not? Truly, I say to you, there will not be left here one stone upon another that will not be thrown down.\'" The prophecy of total destruction is the Christological foreknowledge of the coming judgment (fulfilled in 70 AD when Titus razed the Temple). "Not one stone upon another" is the absolute desolation promised in 23:38. The one who makes this prediction claims the divine foreknowledge of the prophets who predicted Jerusalem\'s earlier falls (Mic 3:12; Jer 26:18). His authority is the authority of the one who governs history.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "As he sat on the Mount of Olives, the disciples came to him privately, saying, \'Tell us, when will these things be, and what will be the sign of your coming and of the end of the age?\'" The private setting on the Mount of Olives — where Zech 14:4 places the eschatological theophany — is the Christological setting for the fifth and final discourse. The disciples\' question collapses three distinct events (Temple destruction, the Son\'s coming, the end of the age) which Jesus will distinguish in his answer. The private teaching to the inner circle continues the pattern of the parable-explanations.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus answered them, \'See that no one leads you astray.\'" The first command of the Olivet Discourse is a Christological warning: the primary danger is deception. False Christs and false signs will create opportunities for astray-going. The one who gives this warning is the only genuine Christ — and the warning itself is a Christological claim: there will be many who claim to be what only he is.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "For many will come in my name, saying, \'I am the Christ,\' and they will lead many astray." The false Christs who come "in my name" — claiming the identity of Jesus — are the Christological parody. The "I am the Christ" claim will be the fraudulent imitation of the genuine confession of 16:16. The Christological standard: the community that has heard the true "I AM" (14:27) can test the false claims against what is authentic.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "And you will hear of wars and rumors of wars. See that you are not alarmed, for this must take place, but the end is not yet." The "must take place" (<em>dei genesthai</em>) is the divine necessity that governs history. The Christological frame: the Son who knows the Father\'s plan can identify what belongs to the "not yet" category. Wars and rumors are not the sign of the end but the condition of the age — the disciples are not to misread them as immediate eschatological triggers.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "For nation will rise against nation, and kingdom against kingdom, and there will be famines and earthquakes in various places." The birth-pains catalog — nation against nation, kingdom against kingdom, famines, earthquakes — is the Christological description of the present age\'s turbulence. These are "the beginning of birth pains" (v.8), not the end itself. The one who governs history names its normal condition: conflict and creation-level disruption that points forward without specifying the exact timing.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "All these are but the beginning of the birth pains." The birth-pain metaphor is the Christological frame for the interadventual period: the new creation is coming, and the present age\'s suffering is the contractions that precede it. The image of birth (Isa 26:17-18; 66:7-9; John 16:20-22) frames suffering as purposive rather than merely destructive. The Son who will rise from the dead introduces the new creation that is being "born" through the age\'s pains.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then they will deliver you up to tribulation and put you to death, and you will be hated by all nations for my name\'s sake." The persecution prediction — "for my name\'s sake" — is the Christological identification of the disciples\' suffering with Christ\'s own. The community that bears his name will face the hatred that he faced (10:22: "you will be hated by all for my name\'s sake"). The passion of the disciples is the extension of the passion of the Lord.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "And then many will fall away and betray one another and hate one another." The falling away (<em>skandalisthēsontai</em>) and mutual betrayal in the community under persecution is the rocky-ground response at a communal scale (cf. 13:21). The Christological warning: the community of Christ will be tested, and the test will reveal who is genuinely rooted. The betrayal of one community member by another is the Judas-pattern replicated — the insider who becomes the enemy under pressure.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "And many false prophets will arise and lead many astray." The false prophets in the community — not outside it but inside — are the second wave of the deception-warning (cf. 7:15: wolves in sheep\'s clothing). The Christological discernment: in the age of tribulation, the community will be assaulted not only from outside (persecution) but inside (false prophecy). The test is the character of the prophet\'s fruit (7:16-20).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "And because lawlessness will increase, the love of many will grow cold." The increase of lawlessness (<em>anomia</em>) that cools love is the Christological description of the spiritual entropy that tribulation and false prophecy produce. Love — the sum of the two great commandments (22:37-39) — is the first casualty of the community under pressure. The Christological counter: the one who loves to the end (John 13:1) is the model and the source of the love that must not grow cold.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "But the one who endures to the end will be saved." The promise of salvation for endurance is the Christological encouragement embedded in the tribulation-warning. The same "end" (<em>telos</em>) that brings judgment brings salvation for those who hold fast. The one who promises salvation has the authority to deliver it — the Son who will endure the cross and be raised on the third day gives the promise of ultimate salvation to those who remain in him.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "And this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed throughout the whole world as a testimony to all nations, and then the end will come." The universal proclamation of the gospel as a precondition of the end is the Christological mission-scope of the Great Commission (28:19). The "gospel of the kingdom" is the announcement of the kingdom that Jesus has inaugurated — the news that the king has come, has died, and has risen. The end follows the completion of the testimony to all nations: the mission is the shape of the interadventual period.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "So when you see the abomination of desolation spoken of by the prophet Daniel, standing in the holy place (let the reader understand)..." The citation of Dan 9:27 (the "abomination that makes desolate") is the Christological hermeneutic of the OT: the prophetic vision is being fulfilled in real historical events. The parenthetical "(let the reader understand)" signals the need for interpretive engagement — this is typological prophecy with a near fulfillment (Jerusalem 70 AD) and perhaps an ultimate eschatological one.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains." The specific, practical instruction — flee to the mountains — is the Christological care for the community\'s physical preservation in the coming judgment. The instruction anticipates the flight of the Jerusalem church before 70 AD. The one who commands flight is the one who knows what is coming; the preservation of the community in the mountains mirrors Noah\'s ark-escape and Lot\'s flight from Sodom.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let the one who is on the housetop not go down to take what is in his house." The urgency of flight — not even stopping to take possessions — is the Christological priority of life over property. The housetop instruction mirrors Lot\'s wife looking back: those who pause for their possessions delay their escape from the judgment. The kingdom\'s eschatological urgency makes all earthly possessions secondary to survival and flight.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "And let the one who is in the field not turn back to take his cloak." The same urgency applied to the fieldworker: no turning back for a cloak. The Christological economy: in the moment of eschatological crisis, the bare minimum of physical preservation takes precedence over every material consideration. The instruction is practical and compassionate — the one who gives it knows the conditions of the coming crisis.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "And alas for women who are pregnant and for those who are nursing infants in those days!" The compassionate recognition of the particular vulnerability of pregnant and nursing mothers in the crisis is the Christological pastoral concern within the eschatological warning. The woe is not judgment on the mothers but grief over the suffering that cannot be avoided. The one who wept over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) names the most vulnerable who will suffer in the coming catastrophe.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Pray that your flight may not be in winter or on a Sabbath." The instruction to pray about the timing of flight — winter (impassable roads) and Sabbath (limited movement under law) — is the Christological integration of prayer and practical eschatology. Prayer shapes events; the community is urged to intercede for conditions that will make the necessary flight possible. The one who instructs prayer knows that prayer is genuine participation in how events unfold.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "For then there will be great tribulation, such as has not been from the beginning of the world until now, no, and never will be." The superlative tribulation — unprecedented and unrepeated — is the Christological framing of the coming judgment on Jerusalem as the nadir of covenantal history. The language echoes Dan 12:1 ("a time of trouble such as never has been"). The one who names this tribulation knows its unique character: the judgment of the generation that rejected the Son, the filling up of the measure (23:32).</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "And if those days had not been cut short, no human being would be saved. But for the sake of the elect those days will be cut short." The shortening of the tribulation "for the sake of the elect" is the Christological protection of the community within the historical catastrophe. The "elect" (<em>eklektoi</em>) are those chosen in Christ; their preservation shapes the duration of the judgment. The Christological sovereignty: the days of tribulation are not determined merely by historical forces but by the Father\'s care for his chosen.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then if anyone says to you, \'Look, here is the Christ!\' or \'There he is!\' do not believe it." The repeated deception-warning about false Christs in the tribulation context is the Christological self-definition by contrast: the genuine Christ does not need to be pointed out in a corner or a wilderness. The very need to say "look, here he is" is the mark of the false — the genuine return of the Son of Man will be unmistakable (v.27).</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "For false christs and false prophets will arise and perform great signs and wonders, so as to lead astray, if possible, even the elect." The false christs\' signs and wonders — genuine miracles in the service of deception — are the Christological warning that miraculous power is not self-authenticating. The standard for authentic messiahship is not signs and wonders but the content of the message and its alignment with the Son\'s actual teaching. Even miracles can be demonically enabled (7:22-23).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "See, I have told you beforehand." The Christological forewarning — "I have told you beforehand" — is itself a Christological claim: the one who tells beforehand is the one with prophetic foreknowledge. The warning is designed to immunize the community against deception: having heard the prediction, they will recognize the counterfeit when it appears. The forewarned community is the protected community.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "So, if they say to you, \'Look, he is in the wilderness,\' do not go out. If they say, \'Look, he is in the inner rooms,\' do not believe it." The two locations — wilderness and inner rooms — are both places of apparent hiddenness and private access. The Christological return will not be hidden or private. The wilderness Jesus was tested in and the inner rooms where he taught the disciples are not the locations of the final revelation of the Son of Man.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "For as the lightning comes from the east and shines as far as the west, so will be the coming of the Son of Man." The lightning-from-east-to-west image of the Son of Man\'s coming is the Christological claim of universal, simultaneous visibility: no one will miss it, no one will be ahead of others in receiving the news, no one will need to be pointed to where it is happening. The parousia is not an event in a corner but a cosmic-scale disclosure that precedes no announcement because it is itself the announcement.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "Wherever the corpse is, there the vultures will gather." The dark proverb — corpse and vultures — applied to the coming judgment is the Christological image of inevitable consequence: death draws its agents, judgment draws its executors. The cosmic judgment of the Son of Man\'s coming will find its objects with the same inevitability that vultures find the dead. The Christological use of the proverb: the judgment is not arbitrary but follows the logic of spiritual death already present.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "Immediately after the tribulation of those days the sun will be darkened, and the moon will not give its light, and the stars will fall from heaven, and the powers of the heavens will be shaken." The cosmic de-creation language — sun darkened, moon eclipsed, stars falling, heavens shaken — is drawn from Isa 13:10 (judgment on Babylon), Joel 2:10 (the day of the LORD), and Isa 34:4. The Christological use: these OT judgment images are applied to the coming of the Son of Man — the eschatological event that all the OT cosmic-disruption language was pointing toward.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then will appear in heaven the sign of the Son of Man, and then all the tribes of the earth will mourn, and they will see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of heaven with power and great glory." The appearance of the Son of Man on the clouds is the direct application of Dan 7:13-14 to Jesus\' personal return. The "sign of the Son of Man" is not a prior sign but the Son of Man himself as the sign. "All the tribes of the earth will mourn" echoes Zech 12:10 (mourning for the one they pierced). The power and great glory are the divine attributes of the one who was humbled at Calvary — the reversal is complete.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he will send out his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of heaven to the other." The gathering of the elect by angels at the trumpet call is the eschatological fulfillment of Isa 27:13 (the great trumpet gathering the dispersed) and the harvest imagery of the parables (13:41-43). The "his angels" and "his elect" are the Christological ownership-claim: the Son of Man\'s angels execute his mission of gathering the community that is his. The gathering is the completion of the mission begun in the Great Commission.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "From the fig tree learn its lesson: as soon as its branch becomes tender and puts out its leaves, you know that summer is near." The fig tree lesson — reading the signs of the season from natural observation — is the Christological call to the same interpretive skill applied to eschatological signs. The one who cursed the barren fig tree (21:19) now uses the budding fig tree as a model of readable signs. Discernment is the skill: reading what the observable indicators are pointing toward.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "So also, when you see all these things, you know that he is near, at the very gates." The "he is near, at the very gates" — the Son of Man at the threshold — is the Christological application of the fig-tree lesson: the signs point to the person. The community that has received the signs-catalog (vv.4-28) can read "all these things" as indicators of the Son\'s approaching arrival. The interpretive skill is not calculation but recognition.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, this generation will not pass away until all these things take place." The "this generation" (<em>hē genea hautē</em>) as the time-reference has generated much debate: does it refer to the generation addressed (70 AD fulfillment), the Jewish race (ethnic continuity), or the end-time generation? In the Matthean context, it most naturally refers to the generation that will see the specific events of vv.15-22 (Jerusalem\'s destruction) — a near-term prediction fulfilled in 70 AD that also has eschatological dimensions.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A direct revelation: "Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away." The Christological authority-claim at its most absolute: the words of Jesus have greater permanence than the created order itself. The creation that passes away at the eschaton (Rev 21:1: "the first heaven and the first earth had passed away") is less permanent than the Son\'s word. This is the claim of the one whose words created the world (John 1:3: "through him all things were made") — the logos whose speech is the most real thing in the universe.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "But concerning that day and hour no one knows, not even the angels of heaven, nor the Son, but the Father only." The Son\'s expressed ignorance of the hour is the Christological humility-claim of the incarnate state: the Son in his human condition has genuinely entered into the kenotic limitation (Phil 2:7: "emptied himself") that includes not knowing the Father\'s specific timing. This is not a denial of omniscience but the genuine human condition of the incarnate Son, who learned obedience through suffering (Heb 5:8) and experienced temporal limitation in his earthly life.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "For as were the days of Noah, so will be the coming of the Son of Man." The Noah typology — the days before the flood as the model for the days before the parousia — is the Christological use of OT narrative as eschatological pattern. Noah\'s generation was not uniquely wicked but uniquely unaware: eating, drinking, marrying until the flood came. The parousia will arrive with the same suddenness in a world carrying on ordinary life.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: "For as in those days before the flood they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day when Noah entered the ark." The ordinary activities — eating, drinking, marrying — are not condemned as sinful but as signs of obliviousness. The Christological warning: the disaster that interrupted ordinary life in Noah\'s day was not preceded by a general sense of doom but by total normalcy. The Son\'s return will interrupt a world that is not expecting it.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they were unaware until the flood came and swept them all away, so will be the coming of the Son of Man." The "unaware until" — the sudden catastrophe — is the Christological urgency of the entire watching-and-readiness section that follows. The unawareness is not intellectual but attitudinal: they knew about Noah\'s warning but did not live in light of it. The community of Christ is called to be the opposite: aware, watching, living in light of the coming.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then two men will be in the field; one will be taken and one left." The sudden differentiation — two in the same place, different outcomes — is the Christological image of the parousia\'s discriminating effect. The same work, the same location, but different destinations at the moment of the Son\'s arrival. The Christological bearing: the community of faith does not visibly differ from the world in ordinary circumstances, but the parousia makes the difference absolute and irreversible.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "Two women will be grinding at the mill; one will be taken and one left." The same differentiation at the mill: the most ordinary domestic labor interrupted by the eschatological event that separates. The Christological pattern repeats across contexts — field and mill, men and women, all equally subject to the sudden discriminating arrival of the Son of Man. The parousia is not a distant religious abstraction but an event that will occur in the middle of ordinary work.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore, stay awake, for you do not know on what day your Lord is coming." The "your Lord" (<em>ho kyrios hymōn</em>) is the Christological title of ownership: the Son of Man is not merely the cosmic judge but the personal Lord of the community that follows him. The watchfulness command — stay awake — is the response to acknowledged ignorance of the timing combined with certainty of the event. The Lord is coming; his servants do not know when; therefore they stay awake.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: "But know this, that if the master of the house had known in what part of the night the thief was coming, he would have stayed awake and would not have let his house be broken into." The homeowner-and-thief analogy makes the case from negative example: the one who would have watched if he had known. The Christological application: since you cannot know when, you must always be ready. The ignorance that led to unpreparedness is the condition the disciples must not be in.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore you also must be ready, for the Son of Man is coming at an hour you do not expect." The "Son of Man is coming" applied to the disciples\' readiness is the personal Christological urgency: the one coming is their Lord, the judge of all, and his arrival at the unexpected hour is the fixed eschatological fact that shapes the entire disposition of the watching community. Readiness is not anxiety but the active expectation of the one who is certainly coming.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: "Who then is the faithful and wise servant, whom his master has set over his household, to give them their food at the proper time?" The faithful-and-wise servant parable opens the final section of the Olivet Discourse — the series of watchfulness parables that continue into ch.25. The servant set over the household is the community leader or disciple entrusted with care of the community. The Christological standard: faithfulness and wisdom are the marks of the servant who truly represents the absent master.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A direct revelation: "Blessed is that servant whom his master will find so doing when he comes." The beatitude for the servant found doing the work when the master returns is the Christological commendation that every disciple seeks. "When he comes" points to the parousia as the moment of evaluation. The one who gives this blessing is the returning master — and the beatitude is his personal promise to those who faithfully discharge the service.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, he will set him over all his possessions." The reward for faithful service is expanded authority — "over all his possessions." The Christological economy of the kingdom: faithfulness with the entrusted portion is rewarded with greater scope. This is the same pattern as the Talents parable (25:21, 23: "I will set you over much"). The returning master\'s reward is participation in the master\'s own resources and authority.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A revelation of God: "But if that wicked servant says to himself, \'My master is delayed..\'" The wicked servant\'s calculus — the master\'s delay justifies present abuse — is the Christological exposure of the heart that watches for the master\'s absence rather than his return. The delay in the parousia becomes the excuse for the exploitation of the community. The Christological warning: those who say "my master is delayed" have already revealed that they are not the faithful servant but his opposite.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A revelation of God: "And begins to beat his fellow servants and eats and drinks with drunkards..." The abuse of fellow servants during the master\'s absence is the Christological definition of unfaithfulness: the entrusted position used for exploitation rather than service. The eating and drinking with drunkards is the abandonment of the sober watchfulness commanded in v.42. The wicked servant\'s behavior is the anti-type of the faithful community.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A direct revelation: "The master of that servant will come on a day when he does not expect him and at an hour he does not know." The unexpected return falling on the unready wicked servant is the Christological irony of the passage: the one who used the master\'s delay as license is caught by the master\'s arrival at precisely the moment of unpreparedness. The return of the Lord is the moment of revelation — revealing what was always true of the servant\'s heart.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A direct revelation: "And will cut him in pieces and put him with the hypocrites. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth." The final eschatological warning of the Olivet Discourse — cut in pieces, placed with the hypocrites, weeping and gnashing — closes the discourse with the consequence of unfaithfulness. The "hypocrites" of the Woes (ch.23) and the wicked servant of the final parable share the same end: the outer darkness where the kingdom\'s pretenders are finally revealed. The one who promises this judgment is the one who will execute it at his return.'
  }
}

